}Here, the JIT can see that even though the  is typed as , it’s always actually an . In that case, dotnet/runtime#111948 enables the return type to be retyped in the JIT as  and the enumerator can be stack allocated.Of course, too much cloning can be a bad thing, in particular as it increases code size. dotnet/runtime#108771 employs a heuristic to determine whether loops that  be cloned  be cloned; the larger the loop, the less likely it’ll be to be cloned.“Inlining”, which replaces a call to a function with a copy of that function’s implementation, has always been a critically important optimization. It’s easy to think about the benefits of inlining as just being about avoiding the overhead of a call, and while that can be meaningful (especially when considering security mechanisms like Intel’s Control-Flow Enforcement Technology, which slightly increases the cost of calls), generally the most benefit from inlining comes from knock-on benefits. Just as a simple example, if you have code like:int i = Divide(10, 5);

static int Divide(int n, int d) => n / d;if  doesn’t get inlined, then when  is called, it’ll need to perform the actual , which is a relatively expensive operation. In contrast, if  is inlined, then the call site becomes:which can be evaluated at compile time and becomes just:More compelling examples were already seen throughout the discussion of escape analysis and stack allocation, which depend heavily on the ability to inline methods. Given the increased importance of inlining, it’s gotten even more focus in .NET 10.Some of the .NET work related to inlining is about enabling more kinds of things to be inlined. Historically, a variety of constructs present in a method would prevent that method from even being considered for inlining. Arguably the most well known of these is exception handling: methods with exception handling clauses, e.g.  or , would not be inlined. Even a simple method like  in this example:// dotnet run -c Release -f net9.0 --filter "*" --runtimes net9.0 net10.0

