of that method doesn’t know how the consumer will be consuming it, and the consumer doesn’t know the details of how the producer produced it. But since the LINQ methods flow context via the concrete implementations of , significant optimizations are possible for interesting combinations of consumer and producer methods. For example, let’s say a producer of an  decides they want to always return data in ascending order, so they do:public static IEnumerable<T> GetData()
{
    ...
    return data.OrderBy(s => s.CreatedAt);
}But as it turns out, the consumer won’t be looking at all of the elements, and instead just wants the first:T value = GetData().First();LINQ optimizes this by having the enumerable returned from  provide a specialized implementation of /: it doesn’t need to perform an  sort (or allocate a lot of memory to hold all of the keys), it can instead just do an  search for the smallest element in the source, because the smallest element would be the first to be yielded from . is ripe for these kinds of optimizations as well, e.g. , , and  all entail non-trivial processing and/or allocation, but if followed by a , all that work can be skipped, as the  can just search the source directly. With dotnet/runtime#112684, this set of optimizations is extended to , with almost 30 specialized implementations of  across the various iterator specializations.// dotnet run -c Release -f net9.0 --filter "*" --runtimes net9.0 net10.0

