{
    string? line = await reader.ReadLineAsync();
    ...
}Now not only might  do I/O and block, it’s doing that in a method that’s supposed to do all of its waiting asynchronously.What makes this even more frustrating is that  isn’t even useful in a loop like that above.  will return a  string if it’s at the end of the stream, so the loop would instead be better as:while (await reader.ReadLineAsync() is string line)
