}This is a simple test where we’re trying to match any positive number of whitespace characters followed by any positive number of non-whitespace characters, giving it an input composed entirely of whitespace. Without atomicity, the engine is going to consume all of the whitespace as part of the  but will then find that there isn’t any non-whitespace available to match the . What does it do then? It backtracks, gives back one of the hundred spaces consumed by , and tries again to match the . It won’t match, so it backtracks again. And again. And again. A hundred times, until it has nothing left to try and gives up. With atomicity, all that backtracking goes away, allowing it to fail faster.dotnet/runtime#117892 is a related improvement. In regex,  is called a “word boundary”; it checks whether the wordness of the previous character (whether the previous character matches ) matches the wordness of the next character, calling it a boundary if they differ. You can see this in the engine’s  helper’s implementation, which follows (note that according to TR18 whether a character is considered a boundary word char is  exactly the same as , except with two additional zero-width Unicode characters also included):internal static bool IsBoundary(ReadOnlySpan<char> inputSpan, int index)
{
    int indexM1 = index - 1;
    return ((uint)indexM1 < (uint)inputSpan.Length && RegexCharClass.IsBoundaryWordChar(inputSpan[indexM1])) !=
           ((uint)index < (uint)inputSpan.Length && RegexCharClass.IsBoundaryWordChar(inputSpan[index]));
}The optimizer already had a special-case in its auto-atomicity logic that had knowledge of boundaries and their relationship to  and , specifically. So, if you had , the optimizer would recognize that in order for the  to match, what comes after what the  matches must necessarily not match , because then it wouldn’t be a boundary, and thus the  could be made atomic. Similarly, with a pattern of , it would recognize that what came after must not be in , and could make the loop atomic. It didn’t generalize this, though. Now in .NET 10, it does. This PR teaches the optimizer how to recognize subsets of , because, as with the special-case of , any subset of  can similarly benefit: if what comes before the  is a word character, what comes after must not be. Thus, with this PR, an expression like  will now have the loop made atomic.// dotnet run -c Release -f net9.0 --filter "*" --runtimes net9.0 net10.0

