}A few other performance niceties have also found their way in.. dotnet/runtime#106728 and dotnet/runtime#112638 add and then use throughout the crypto stack a callback-based mechanism to  that enables encoding without forced allocation for the temporary encoded state.. dotnet/runtime#109391 employs a singleton  in more places in  to avoid temporary handle allocation.. dotnet/runtime#109529 from @ChadNedzlek adds -based overloads to the  class that enable protecting data without requiring the source or destinations to be in allocated arrays.. dotnet/runtime#109438 adds UTF-8 support to . , a utility class for parsing and formatting PEM (Privacy-Enhanced Mail)-encoded data such as that used in certificates and keys, previously worked only with s. As was then done in dotnet/runtime#109564, this change makes it possible to parse UTF8 data directly without first needing to transcode to UTF16.. dotnet/runtime#109130 adds an X509Certification2Collection.FindByThumbprint method. The implementation uses a stack-based buffer for the thumbprint value for each candidate certificate, eliminating the arrays that would otherwise be created in a naive manual implementation. dotnet/runtime#113606 then utilized this in .dotnet/runtime#113146 adds a span-based SymmetricAlgorithm.SetKey method which can then be used to avoid creating unnecessary arrays.As in every .NET release, there are a large number of PRs that help with performance in some fashion. The more of these that are addressed, the more the overall overhead for applications and services is lowered. Here are a smattering from this release:. DATAS (Dynamic Adaptation To Application Sizes) was introduced in .NET 8 and enabled by default in .NET 9. Now in .NET 10, dotnet/runtime#105545 tuned DATAS to improve its overall behavior, cutting unnecessary work, smoothing out pauses (especially under high allocation rates), correcting fragmentation accounting that could cause extra short collections (gen1), and other such tweaks. The net result is fewer unnecessary collections, steadier throughput, and more predictable latency for allocation-heavy workloads. dotnet/runtime#118762 also adds several knobs for configuring how DATAS behaves, and in particular settings to fine-tune how Gen0 grows.. The GC supports various types of “handles” that allow for explicit management of resources in relation to GC operation. For example, you can create a “pinning handle,” which ensures that the GC will not move the object in question. Historically, these handles were surfaced to developers via the  type, but it has a variety of issues, including that it’s really easy to misuse due to lack of strong typing. To help address that, dotnet/runtime#111307 introduces a few new strongly-typed flavors of handles, with , , and . These should not only address some of the usability issues, they’re also able to shave off a bit of the overheads incurred by the old design.
